air a similar one to which is shown in relief in the tomb of Queen Meresankh III figure 39.";i:12;s:121:"These carrying chairs are of frame and panel construction and are attached to a pair of long poles which have handles of.";i:13;s:96:"Armchair of Queen Hetepheres I The seat and the backrest of this chair are made of natural wood.";i:14;s:98:"They are surrounded by a simple wooden frame covered with gold leaf with high arms in gilded wood.";i:15;s:73:"The backrest of the chair is reinforced at the rear by a central support.";i:16;s:128:"Ornate arm chairs made of wood with overlaid gold and silver were found in the tombs of Queen Hetepheres I and King Tutankhamen.";i:17;s:107:"These arm chairs features strong lines and exquisite detail including carved lotus flowers and animal legs.";i:18;s:137:"In 1926 an American archaeological mission supervised by Harvard University and Boston University unearthed the tomb of Queen Hetepheres.";i:19;s:207:"They uncovered her belongings which included pieces of funerary furniture like a carrying chair bed and actual chair in addition to a number of her personal belongings such as accessories according to Hamed.";i:20;s:33:"Queen Hetepheres IQueen of Egypt.";i:21;s:55:"Actual chair of Queen Hetepheres from the Cairo Museum.";i:22;s:136:"Burialtomb G 7000X near the Great Pyramid of GizaSpouseSneferuIssuePrincess Hetepheres KhufuFatherHuniReligionAncient Egyptian religion.";i:23;s:62:"Queen Hetepheres I was a Queen of Egyptduring the 4th dynasty.";i:24;s:40:"BiographyEdit Hetepheres in hieroglyphs.";i:25;s:30:"Carryng chair of Hetepheres I.";i:26;s:42:"This object was a gift from her son Khufu.";i:27;s:64:"Hetepheres I Her Face Is Satisfied was a Queen of Ancient Egypt.";i:28;s:89:"She lived during the 4th dynasty of Egypt but she was born at the end of the 3rd dynasty.";i:29;s:158:"Hetepheres ancient Egyptian queen wife of the king Snefru who bore the title Daughter of God and represented the direct royal blood line of the 4th dy